id="dsq-comment-body-2531" class="dsq-comment-body"><div
id="dsq-comment-message-2531" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>@Koos</p><p>Thanks for your great work.</p><p>Just wondered if you had an opinion on the following?</p><p>I have been trying to figure where we are going by looking at where we have been. The<br
/> starting point for my research has been why the US ceased auditing their gold<br
/> reserves in 1955?</p><p>Could it be as simple as:</p><p>Vietnam War<br
/> (part of the Start of the Cold War) 1954 &#8211; 1975<br
/> -&gt;Dramatic US<br
/> borrowing and resulting FED money printing to fund Military<br
/> -&gt;Foreign Nations converting US holdings to gold heavily in late 60s early 70&#8242;s due to US<br
/> concerns<br
/> -&gt;Nixon removes gold standard in 1971<br
/> -&gt;1974: media show footage of US gold in order to calm public concern<br
/> -&gt;Fiat printing spree from 1971-1975 to fund the final leg of the war.<br
/> -&gt;Soviet War in Afghanistan 1979 &#8211; 1989<br
/> -&gt;Reagan appoints gold commission 1981 as potential way to restore faith in USD<br
/> -&gt;Reagans commission finds gold standard unnecessary 1982<br
/> -&gt;Was there not enough US gold in 1982 to restart the gold standard, whilst maintaining<br
/> control and exorbitant privilege?<br
/> -&gt;Did the US have to ramp the fear and threat of the Cold War to scare the West into<br
/> accepting the fiat USD&#8230;or else deal with USSR on their own.<br
/> -&gt;When the last major threat (Soviet Union) collapsed, Gold was no longer necessary, and<br
/> &#8220;King Dollar&#8221; began.</p><p>Assumptions</p><p>1. The US went off the gold standard so they could print all the money they wanted under fiat<br
/> in order to survive the financially dire period of the Cold War &amp;</p><p>2. If UK and Euro agreed to avoid gold to benefit from fiat and in order for them to have<br
/> protection under the west allegiance powers.</p><p>Q: where did US/UK/Euros gold go? Did approx 10,000MT go to the public in drip feed from<br
/> 1971 to present? &amp;</p><p>If China is buying gold, but the majority voters of the IMF (US/UK/Euro) have little to no<br
/> gold, why would the IMF push toward a partial gold backed SDR?</p><p>I&#8217;m starting to think Chinas gold may have an alternate purpose.</p><p>Any thoughts?</p><p>Dark Horse</p></div></div><ul
